HANTAVIRUS UPDATE - AMERICAS (23): USA (COLORADO) REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
*************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 21 May 2015
Source: The Daily Sentinel [edited]
http://www.gjsentinel.com/news/articles/officials-report-8232hantavirus-case-in-garco


Health officials are reporting a recent case of [a] hantavirus [infection] in western Garfield County, in what's serving as a reminder of the particular risk the mouseborne disease can pose during spring-cleaning season. Garfield County Public Health and the Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment are investigating the case. A county news release didn't provide information on the victim's age, gender, hometown or condition.

This is the 2nd case in the county in 2 years. Last year a Silt resident survived after contracting the disease, which has close to a 40 per cent mortality rate.

Hantavirus[es] are carried [shed] in the saliva, urine and droppings of certain infected mice found in the western and central United States. Most human infections result from breathing in [a] hantavirus that becomes airborne when contaminated dust and dirt are stirred up, although transmission also can occur by a bite from an infected mouse.

Yvonne Long, Garfield County's public health director, said in a news release, "If you have mice in or around your home, barns, or cabins you are at risk for exposure to hantavirus[es]. That is why we are urging people to exercise extreme caution when they enter or clean up an area with evidence of rodents." Authorities advise against sweeping or vacuuming areas where mice have been present. Instead, they say to use protective gloves, wet down areas with a solution of 1 part bleach to 9 parts water, and keep the area wet for 5 minutes before beginning cleanup. Dead mice should be sealed in plastic bags before disposal.

Health officials also recommend mouse-proofing homes through measures such as storing food in rodent-proof containers, plugging holes and other entryways, removing outside wood and junk piles and abandoned vehicles where mice may hide, and trapping or poisoning mice inside homes or hiring an exterminator.

Symptoms of hantavirus [infections] typically take 2-4 weeks after exposure to appear. Early symptoms include fatigue, fever and muscle aches, and other symptoms can include headaches, dizziness, chills and abdominal problems. Within 1-5 days after symptoms begin, coughing and difficulty breathing occurs [hantavirus pulmonary symdrome].

There is no specific treatment, cure or vaccine for hantavirus, but prompt treatment may improve the chance for recovery.

[byline: Dennis Webb]

