[Although not stated in the report above, the specific hantavirus involved in this and the previous hantavirus pulmonary syndrome cases in Colorado probably is Sin Nombre virus, which is endemic in deer mice (_Peromyscus maniculatus_) there. Although cases of Sin Nombre virus infection are relatively rare, they can be very serious, as the 3 HPS deaths in Colorado this year (2015) indicate. The pubic needs to be aware of the circumstances that lead to risk of virus transmission. This is particularly important at this spring season of the year, when cabins and other outbuildings that have been closed for several months, are reopened and cleaned out, raising dust that may be contaminated with virus from deer mice hosts. ProMED-mail would appreciate receiving additional information about the condition and outcome of the above case and the dates of the illness.

An image of the deer mouse, _P. maniculatus_, can be seen at the URL above and at http://www.nsf.gov/news/mmg/media/images/mouse_f.jpg.

The US state of Colorado can be located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3380955,6666. Garfield County can be seen on the map at http://geology.com/county-map/colorado-county-map.gif. - Mod.TY]
